replies.text:
@drakoan 
You sound a lot like me. I learned quite a few masking behaviors when I was younger, and I still use them. I know a lot of folks with ASD have difficulty with sarcasm, but I'm one of the "lucky ones" who doesn't, and I was able to turn a lot of my "socially inappropriate" comments into snark...it's helped me smooth over plenty of instances of putting my foot all the way into my mouth. I think it also helps that I have no problem being incredibly self-deprecating. Unintentionally rude comments tend to have less sting when the person who made the comment routinely says much worse things about themselves, apparently. 

That being said, despite years of learning how to say and do socially acceptable things while limiting my socially unacceptable comments and actions, for the life of me, I still don't actually understand those things, nor why they're socially acceptable or not.

